While driving, I spotted the Harris's Hawk perched on top of a telephone pole. When I stopped the car to look at it with binoculars, I noticed that directly across the street, a Red-shouldered Hawk was perched on top of the opposite telephone pole, eating freshly caught prey. Between bites, the Red-shouldered Hawk kept glancing over at the Harris's Hawk, and the Harris's Hawk let out a screech every minute or two. I got out of the car to photograph it and it flew to a tree half a block away, where it sat for several minutes before taking off and flying out of sight. However, it returned about 5 minutes later and landed on top of another telephone pole where it sat for a few minutes, and then flew out of sight again.

Stakeout—Merlin nest—Bedford Rd, Upper Arlington US-OH (39.9973,-83.0568)
Observation Details: Nestwatch; FIVE recently fledged young, approximately 26-30 days old. Upon arrival at 8:00 they were dispersed and tough to find in the dense canopy of ginkgo and maple. We could find what I assumed were the three young I had barely seen the heads of in the nest a week ago. It was pretty quiet until 9:00 when adults brought in food, and suddenly there were FOUR lined up on one limb! The FIFTH and presumed youngest was still by the nest but watching his nestmates closely and is close to being able to make the leap from the ginkgo to the maple. We watched the female bring in two birds and saw two fledglings pluck prey and eat. The young birds seemed content to wait their turn and never crowded the feeding bird. A lot of down was sifting out as the juvenile birds preened. We had a scope set up and showed the birds to neighbors and kids passing by.

Locality: FL, Punta Gorda, River Ranch CT

Observation Details: This bird was reported without many details to Maine Audubon in the past day or so. Doug Hitchcox and Fyn Kynd followed up on this report and amazingly found the bird this morning. I arrived in the early afternoon and saw the bird after a brief scan at the intersection of King Street and The Ln. The bird was to the south-southwest over the trees along the Dennys River. It dropped out of sight; so I looked along Route 86 to the west. Shortly after crossing the Dennys River, I spotted the bird over the trees at the edge of a field and bordering the river.  This is one of those birds that is instantly recognizable by shape and pattern--an elegant long-winged raptor with a deeply forked tail. The upperparts and tail were blackish; the underparts, including entire head, were snowy white. In good light, I could see a darker, blackish bar across the leading portion of the upper wing. The secondaries seemed shiny and glossed with a slightly paler grayish bloom. There were times when these dark feathers of the upperwing seemed to be glossed purplish or bluish. Eventually, we saw the bird directly overhead at close range and could see small yellowish to pinkish-yellow feet, a dark gray bill with a pale gray to blue gray cere. The eyes were dark red. The underwing pattern was distinctive in being snowy white across the wing linings (lesser, median, and greater coverts of underwing). The rest of the wing, the remiges, were black, as was the entire tail.  The bird played on the wind as it hunted flying insects. The kite sometimes made rapid banks and turns to zero in on prey. I could not actually see any of the prey, but when the bird grabbed something (apparently) it reached forward with its feet and met them with its beak. It appeared to consume its prey on the wing. As photos show, these were small flying insects (not dragonflies or damselflies as far as I could tell). The bird seemed to find most of its prey over the tops of the trees, but occasionally much higher.  After meeting some locals, I learned that the bird had been seen by them since about September 7 (a rainy day that coincided with the remnants of hurricane Dorian passing east of here into Nova Scotia). This may be coincidence given other recent northerly Swallow-tailed Kites well away from the storms influence.

The head was overall fairly round, with a darkish cap and dark “mustache”, as well as a whitish throat. The bird also had a brownish eye, and mostly yellow bill with a dark hooked tip. The breast was an overall mottled reddish brown color with a white base, with mottling becoming more sparse as well as more barred towards the belly and flanks, giving way to a mostly white belly and vent. The wings and back were an overall medium brown color with most feathers becoming paler towards the edges. In flight the bird had a very dark almost black border on the wings extending from the primaries down through the trailing edge of the wing all the way to the tail. We remarked that this edging was somewhat reminiscent of a Gray Hawk. The underwing was overall lightly patterned, with light brownish mottling becoming lighter and more barred towards the trailing edge of the wing. The tail feathers were also strikingly marked with black and white bands.

Adult Broad-winged Hawk, present since photographed by Scott Paladichuk on16 February 2021, here photographed in flight by Curtis A. Marantz on 17 February at Pinecrest Park, Mission Viejo, Orange County, California.
Observation Details: Given that others were already looking at this bird when I arrived, I saw this bird shortly after my arrival at the park; however, over time, this bird moved about extensively, and we lost it for moderate periods of time before somebody invariably relocated some distance from where we had last seen it.  Over time, I was able to get good views and some good photos as it perched in various trees and for an extended period of time on a large steel construct atop the hillside to the east of the canyon.  During my visit, this bird moved back-and-forth across the canyon, perching in trees on both sides of the canyon and even moving into the neighborhood to the west of the park.  Others apparently saw this bird take a bird from a yard and at one point we saw it drop to the ground to take what appeared to be a gopher that we later saw it kill and eat. This was a relatively small hawk that when seen in direct comparison was only two-thirds to three-quarters the size of a Common Raven that eventually displaced it, yet I suspect its body mass was no more than half that of the raven.  This bird’s structure was that of a Buteo, and a rather compact one at that.  The bill was relatively small for a hawk, in that it would have extended backward on the face to a point at or maybe just behind the eye, and it tapered from a base of medium depth to a hooked tip along a culmen that was sharply curved distally.  The forehead was conspicuously steep and the rounded head had a somewhat domed appearance with the peak roughly above the eye.  I also thought this bird’s head seemed larger in proportion to the body than do those of the larger buteos.  The neck was relatively short and inconspicuous, and the body was plump, full-chested, and with a posture that appeared a little more upright than diagonal with the tail held downward in the plane of the body.  The wings were relatively long, with the tapered wingtip falling ever so slightly short of the tip of the tail, and with the tips of four primaries extending beyond the longest tertials in tapered wingtips in which the primary projection was about 125% the length of the exposed tertials.  I thought the tail was approximately as long as the body without the head or neck, which was at the shorter end of the spectrum for a Buteo.  The tail appeared to be parallel-sided and essentially square-tipped when held closed, when the corners were slightly rounded.  The legs were unfeathered but unremarkable for a medium-sized hawk in both their length and mass.  The claws were relatively long and hooked.  My views of the flying bird were rather superficial, yet I thought the wings were relatively long and broad at least basally, and also that the tail was of medium length. This was a well-marked, but not overly colorful bird.  The forehead, crown, nape, and face were medium-brown and only subtly marked.  Close inspection revealed that the lores were dull whitish from the base of the upper mandible back almost to the leading edge of the eye, and this same color appeared to extend so narrowly across the forehead that this was difficult to see except under the best conditions.  I thought the crown may have had darker streaking, but I could not really be sure; however, we repeatedly noted that the nape had white streaking that presumably reflected paler bases to the feathers.  My impression was that the auriculars were unmarked and a slightly paler and maybe subtly more grayish shade of the brown than the crown and superciliary region, and I also generally thought there was a narrow eyering that was about the same shade of dull whitish as the lores.  Photos that I saw of this bird taken the day before I saw it seemed to show a relatively conspicuous malar-stripe, but in the field, I thought the malar region was only subtly darker than the sides of the face.  The darker malar region did demarcate relatively sharply a dull whitish to light gray throat that at times appeared to have a narrow, dark band running from the chin at least most of the way to the junction with the upper breast.  The breast and sides were primarily a dull rufous color with whitish mottling that was inconspicuous, but as one continued down the breast and onto the foreflanks the dull rufous was more conspicuously marked with whitish, and by the belly and flanks, the background was cream-colored with relatively narrow, well-defined, and somewhat wavy bars of the same shade of rufous that characterized the breast.  The lower belly beginning at roughly the insertion points of the legs was cream colored to pale buff and unmarked, and this same color extended through the undertail coverts, though at least some of the latter had darker shaft-streaks.  I never clearly saw the underside of the tail on a bird on which the undertail coverts appeared to reach almost halfway out the tail. Returning to the upperparts, this bird was a relatively dark brown throughout the back and wings.  The back feathers were each a dusky brown color with a moderately well-defined fringe that was warm brown and not all that much lighter than the center on the mantle, but paler and more grayish on the larger and more clearly scaly scapular feathers.  The wing coverts likewise had dusky-brown centers that contrasted with relatively narrow but also moderately well-defined fringes of light grayish-buff that extended along the edges and around the tips of the feathers.  On the larger greater coverts, I thought the pattern was slightly more complex, with the centers a lighter and maybe more grayish brown basally but blending to sooty-brown distally, and again with the narrow fringes that extended along the edges and more obviously across the tips, where also paler and more grayish.  I am not sure I ever clearly saw the alula or primary coverts in the closed wing.  The secondaries had a pattern much like that on the greater coverts, given the paler bases and duskier distal parts in the center, combined with the paler fringes that I recall being more obvious as tips than edges.  The tertials again had the bicolored centers, but the fringes were more obvious, and this was particularly true of the paler and more grayish tips of the feathers.  I thought the exposed primary tips were sooty brown with only relatively inconspicuous fringes of pale buff at the tips of most of the feathers, but seemingly less so on the longest feathers.  I am not sure I ever clearly saw the rump and uppertail coverts, which were obscured by the closed wings when the bird was perched, but I did see the tail relatively well.  I noted on the upperside of the tail at least three blackish bands, with the distal band covering about the distal third of the tail, the middle band quite a bit narrower and near the center of the tail, and the innermost band even narrower.  Separating these birds were paler bands that on the broadest, subterminal band appeared to be whiter in the inner webs but pale gray to brownish-gray on the more easily seen outer webs, an with both webs the latter color on the central feathers that were most easily seen on the upperside of the closed tail.  I thought the pale bands separating the two inner, black bands were similarly colored, but I also did not see them as well.  I noted only a very narrow fringe of pale buff to the tip of the tail.  Although my views of flying bird were brown and rather superficial, I nevertheless noted that the underwings were mostly quite pale, possibly whitish or probably more likely pale buff, and with a narrow yet conspicuous frame of black.  I also saw several whitish and black bands on the upperside of the tail, but the precise pattern eluded me. The bill appeared to be mostly if not entirely black, but the cere was lemon-yellow.  The irides were a warm, medium-brown in color that was light enough to contrast conspicuously with the black pupils.  The legs and feet were lemon-yellow and the claws were blackish, if not truly black.

Observation Details: I was driving roads south of the Cedar Rapids Airport en route to pick up a friend at the airport around 1:15 PM.  While driving along Linn Johnson Rd NW I happened to see a stand of white pine on a farmstead on the south side of the road (Johnson Co.) with a large accipiter perched out in the wide open.  Luckily, I had been birding earlier and I had my camera with me.  As I approached the bird nothing in my mind/searching pattern was triggered i.e. I knew it was too big to be a Cooper's Hawk.  I was able to photograph the juvenile bird.  It was very white and appeared rather long in length (from head to tail) on approach.  Photos revealed very large wings like a buteo, a white supercilium, the outer wings have rufous coloration/speckling, the tail-bands are uneven (with the light bands being thicker than the dark ones and also with some thin white edging between the light and dark bands, but not apparent on the last couple terminating bands), and pale bars were located on the greater coverts.  As it flew away from me it tore back into the property into some thicker foliage.  I noticed the base of its tail was much broader than a Cooper's Hawk, even without binoculars.  Photos were confirmed by JF in the field as I coincidentally ran into him later that day.

Locality: Jamie Hill's Waterford, PA, Pond Property
Observation Details: This immature male accidentally flew into my huge picture window, placed just 25 feet from my bird feeder where there were easily 75 birds feeding (mostly MODOs) when the accipiter swooped in.  The bird was badly stunned and fell head-first into the deep snow below the window.  Only its tail feathers were showing. I doubt it could have ever freed itself buried so deep in the snow, headfirst.  I assumed the bird was dead it hit the window so hard.  I dug it out and it made no attempt to escape. At first, based on its size, I assumed it was a large, female Cooper's Hawk.  I put the bird in a large, brown paper bag and brought it into the warmth of the house.  Twice, over the rest of the day, I tried releasing it, but it just fluttered along the ground and couldn't get airborne.   I kept it overnight and tried releasing it again the following day, with the same results.  The final time I ran after it to recapture it, it grabbed me with its talons and drew blood through my gloves!  I was just going to let nature take its course, but decided to make arrangements to take it to our local wildlife rehabilitation center, Tamarack Wildlife Rehabilitation Center in Saegertown, PA.  When Carol Holmgren of Tamarack weighed it and it came in over 800 grams, she knew, after consulting Pile's Bird Banding Guide, that it was several hundred grams too heavy even for a large, female Cooper's Hawk.  It was in the normal range for a male goshawk.  Closer examination showed the heavily streaked under tail coverts, and the characteristic tail banding pattern with white edging to the darker bands.  My photos were sent off to several experts (Dr. Laurie Goodrich from Hawk Mt. Sanctuary, Jerry McWilliams and Scott Stoleson) who were all 100% certain it was a Northern Goshawk.  They also mentioned the bird had the characteristic robust body, small head, and broad base to the tail.  This individual NOGO had a very indistinct, white supercillium, normally characteristic of the species.  This is why, at first, I assumed this bird was an immature, female Cooper's Hawk.  [Update:  This bird survived and was released into the wild after about 6 weeks of rehab at Tamarack.  This was the first Northern Goshawk Tamarack had ever gotten in!]

**RARE | Continuing bird first seen yesterday, 29 September 2016. I first found this bird in the northern  part of the airport sitting on the Medway Road fence line around 1350. The bird stayed on the airport side of Medway Road throughout the time I was there. When I left around 1615, the bird had moved closer to the airport offices, and was foraging out in the fields of the runway area.  Behavior: Would perch on fence or on ground. Hunted for most of the time I was there, successfully catching insects, typically grasshoppers, and other unidentified prey. Often would run on the ground, as well as flying down from a perch on the fence to capture prey. At one point the bird took off circled a few times gaining elevation, and plummeted in a dive. On 4 or 5 occasions, the bird would fly up to the fence directly in front of us, and allow for fantastic opportunities to study this bird up close. There no reason to approach rare birds beyond a respectable point, but this bird would fly in to distances that were much closer than I feel comfortable getting to a rare bird. It was an amazing experience with a stunning bird.

**continuing local rarity. First spotted at 9:05am. it came in low from the west, presumably where it roosted last night. It circled low over the southern half of the open space, at one point flying right overhead while I was standing in the middle crossroads. Medium-sized, long-winged, slaty-gray Buteo. I lost it to the south at about 9:20 AM. It seems David Buckley saw the bird simultaneously as I did from  a different vantage point: https://ebird.org/checklist/S85966659

Spied a large white marked hawk on the ground some distance away over a berm and went marching quickly in the general direction it disappeared walking behind a large tumbleweed. It then took flight flushed by a dog walker and circled, sometimes hovering like a giant kestrel, and then circled at low elevation over to a snaggy eucalyptus in the center of the dog run area at south end of Fiesta Island.  It is a large very attractive looking hawk, milky and buffy white on the underparts with odd dark spots and arrows, large pale eye, fine brown streaked head, long yellow gape beneath eye.  Amazing upperparts coloration without rust red but instead with dark stone brown back and wings, darker subterminal banding on the flight feathers, and large milky white rump extending in pale coloration down the tail the end more colorfully marked. Pale whitish windows in the primaries. Very eye catching hawk - wow, wow, WOW! Got some amazing photos at close range.
